Don't be intimidated by the wait. The restaurant is super organized and with 11 parties ahead of us on a Thursday morning, we were seated within a half hour. This Louisiana inspired cuisine is just as good as some of the food I tasted when visiting NOLA. I ordered the beignet sampler. I had a taste of the crawfish, chocolate and regular. They were okay. I ended up eating the filling of the crawfish beignet but couldn't finish the beignet. I was REALLY impressed by the shrimp and grits. The shrimps were big and plentiful and the grits were delicious with cheese and chunky bacon bits. The waiter suggested it with a biscuit on the side. The biscuit was okay but needed a bit more salt. I'd come back here but skip all the extras and just order shrimp and grits. Some of the other offerings on the menu sounded delicious as well. Next time I'm in town, I'll have to try that chicken. A neighboring table ordered it and it looked amazing.

Parlez-vous Soul? Parlez-vous Soul Food? Brenda does. This beacon of Creole in the heart of San Francisco dishes up heaping helpings of comfort food for the soul (la nourriture de l'âme). My mom didn't like Brenda's at all, but I did. I really did. My wife did, too. I still love my momma; however, this is my review and she's gonna have to accept her son for his life choices ... cause I'm a fan of Brenda's French Soul Food. The wait was about 25 minutes on a Friday night which wasn't too bad at all. It's a crowded and loud joint (put your name on the chalkboard as soon as you enter to get on the list), so, don't come expecting a romantic dinner for two. The hostess and our server were genuine and efficient. * Crawfish Beignet ($2.75) - Our starter was a popular meaty beignet oozing a blend of Crawfish, Cheese, Cayenne Pepper, and Scallions. It was slightly overcooked, but still was worth getting again. (4 stars) * Kickass Meatloaf ($14.75) - One of the daily specials was a spicy mound of Beef laden with Caramelized Onions and paired with Mashed Potatoes & Gravy and Sauteed Veggies. The spices and onions overwhelmed the meat ... which actually really worked for me. (4 stars) * Cream Biscuit ($1.95) - My gut reaction was that this biscuit was way too dry. The cream biscuit needed more cream; however, the more I ate bites, I started to like it more. Serving honey would of been a nice touch. These biscuits are huge and good for sharing. (3 stars) * Shrimp and Grits ($13) - Seven Sauteed Shrimp on a bowl of gooey Cheddar Grits lathered with a Spicy Tomato Bacon Gravy was on of the reasons we went to Brenda's, so, it was obvious we'd try it. The grits were creamy and the cheese was cheesy. The overall flavor was sweet while the shrimp were ok. (3 stars) * BFC - Brenda's Fried Chicken ($15.75) - This was the best of the best at Brenda's. Olivia Z. said it was some of the best fried chicken she's ever tasted. Three pieces of Brenda's secret recipe fried chicken come in an order. What's the secret? I don't know, but the result is juicy chicken, crispy skin, and very little grease. The BFC dinner comes with a Biscuit and side of Collard Greens. Even if I got a different entree, I'd probably add a piece of BFC cause it was that good. (5 stars) * Beignets Sampler ($6) - For dessert, we split a plate of 3 beignets: Plain (w/Powdered Sugar), Ghirardelli Chocolate, and Granny Smith Apple. Each beignet is large. Plan to share. My favorite was the Apple, but they weren't really magical. A-ok. (3 stars) Parlez-vous Yum? Brenda's French Soul Food does.

As one of the most raved about places in SF, I made it my priority to come by here during my visit. On a Saturday morning at 10am, the boyfriend and I easily found metered street parking along Polk Street. My local friend advised us to do take-out due to the hour long waits, but when I went inside to inquire about the wait time, the host told me it was 15 minutes for take out and 30 minutes for seat in. A lady next to me overheard and insisted that it was worth waiting half an hour for a seat, so I wrote my name up on their chalkboard. The wait went by fairly quick and we were seated within the estimated 30 minutes. The high ceilings and open atmosphere provided a happy environment to eat at. We decided to share the Crawfish Beignets ($9) and Hangtown Fry ($11). The crawfish beignets were the main reason that people come here, so I was really excited to try it. Although tasty, I felt like it could've used less breading so I could taste more of the crawfish flavor. It was worth a try, nonetheless. On the other hand, I really enjoyed the Hangtown Fry. It consisted of oyster, scallion, and bacon scramble with hash. You really taste the oysters in there, which was a pleasant surprise for me. It also came with a side of wheat toast, which complimented the scramble eggs very nicely. In the end, we couldn't finish either dishes and had to box them to go. Brenda's has good portions and tasty food, but not exactly as extraordinary as I had hyped it up to be. I would still love to try some of the other items on their menu at another point.

    * Crawfish Beignet ($2.75) - Our starter was a popular meaty beignet oozing a blend of Crawfish, Cheese, Cayenne Pepper, and Scallions. It was slightly overcooked, but still was worth getting again. (4 stars)

    * Kickass Meatloaf ($14.75) - One of the daily specials was a spicy mound of Beef laden with Caramelized Onions and paired with Mashed Potatoes & Gravy and Sauteed Veggies. The spices and onions overwhelmed the meat ... which actually really worked for me. (4 stars)

    * Shrimp and Grits ($13) - Seven Sauteed Shrimp on a bowl of gooey Cheddar Grits lathered with a Spicy Tomato Bacon Gravy was on of the reasons we went to Brenda's, so, it was obvious we'd try it. The grits were creamy and the cheese was cheesy. The overall flavor was sweet while the shrimp were ok. (3 stars)

    * BFC - Brenda's Fried Chicken ($15.75) - This was the best of the best at Brenda's. Olivia Z. said it was some of the best fried chicken she's ever tasted. Three pieces of Brenda's secret recipe fried chicken come in an order. What's the secret? I don't know, but the result is juicy chicken, crispy skin, and very little grease. The BFC dinner comes with a Biscuit and side of Collard Greens. Even if I got a different entree, I'd probably add a piece of BFC cause it was that good. (5 stars)

    * Beignets Sampler ($6) - For dessert, we split a plate of 3 beignets: Plain (w/Powdered Sugar), Ghirardelli Chocolate, and Granny Smith Apple. Each beignet is large. Plan to share. My favorite was the Apple, but they weren't really magical. A-ok. (3 stars)

    The high ceilings and open atmosphere provided a happy environment to eat at. We decided to share the Crawfish Beignets ($9) and Hangtown Fry ($11). The crawfish beignets were the main reason that people come here, so I was really excited to try it. Although tasty, I felt like it could've used less breading so I could taste more of the crawfish flavor. It was worth a try, nonetheless. On the other hand, I really enjoyed the Hangtown Fry. It consisted of oyster, scallion, and bacon scramble with hash. You really taste the oysters in there, which was a pleasant surprise for me. It also came with a side of wheat toast, which complimented the scramble eggs very nicely. In the end, we couldn't finish either dishes and had to box them to go. Brenda's has good portions and tasty food, but not exactly as extraordinary as I had hyped it up to be. I would still love to try some of the other items on their menu at another point.

The creamiest, not to mention cheesiest grits, I've ever had and the  eight or so shrimp were perfectly cooked. The sauce has good sized pieces of bacon that my pescatarian leaning wife was able to put aside (more for me yay) and lovely chunks of soft tomatoes.  Our third ordered red beans and rice with an andouille sausage. Very tasty and again a huge portion. We also ordered two biscuits because, well they were biscuits. They were perfection, served with some lovely strawberry compote with a subtle spice.  Our only regret is we had no room for any of the desserts. They all looked epic.   Seemed a bit shy on the vegetarian and pescatarian options, if the shrimp and grits could be served without the bacon, it would be a good move. Everything we had was memorable and delicious, our server Bianca was very good, friendly and commiserating with our inability to fit in dessert. We'll be back
